@ds84182 this isn't a fidelity - performance trade off, this is just a fidelity - fidelity trade off. Today you can either run at a device appropriate framerate (90hz/60hz) during the transition, or you can run animations but at a significantly reduced frame rate. Obviously we'd prefer to run at the full frame rate, with as rich of transitions as possible but that is not possible today.
@flar If you suspect that we could still get good frame rates by using this rasterized transform layer or (ideally) by fixing image filter, then I think you should prioritize working on it and compare that benchmark with the numbers I have above.
I had a previous PR that had a more targeted heursitc fix for this, but in retrospect I think that is actually a bad idea. What happens when the next android version has a page transition that does a spin and fade mixed with a color blending effect? How long would the framework team need to wait for the engine team to adjust their heustics? toGpuImage gives the framework the ability to take performance into their own hands, which is important given that our priorities don't always line up.

@flar I think some of these questions might be better suited in some dedicated issues. When implementing flutter/engine#33736 I did run a number of test cases manually to try to simulate the things you're suggesting. It's quite possible I missed something or that there are bugs in the implementation.
In general, the GPU image will throw when you try to draw it to the canvas if there was a problem. I tried some test cases manually that should have exercised loss of GPU context, but it's quite possible that I didn't exercise it correctly.
In any case, for the cases in this patch, when the GrContext is restored you'd be generating a new image anyway - this only really happens today when the app goes to background and comes back.

